result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: for Plea & Sentencing Hearing held June 13, 2016.  (Kimberly R. Collins, Court Reporter)
Defendant Ricki A Hankins in court with attorney Emily M Nolan-Plutchak.  Michael Daniel Zell appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Disimissed and read in.
Plea hearing on June 13, 2016 at 10:00 am.
Jury trial - 12 person on June 29, 2016 at 08:15 am.
to Extend Deadline for Prompt Disposition Request or to Allow the State to Dismiss the Matter without Prejudice

Defendant Ricki A Hankins #403204 in court with attorney Emily M Nolan-Plutchak.  Defendant Ricki A Hankins #403204 in custody.  Michael Daniel Zell appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Officer Scott DeWitt is sworn and questioned by Attorney Zell. Testifies to being dispatched to a business and speaking with the owner regarding a complaint of defendant keeping checks that belonged to the business.  Testifies to the specifics of who wrote the checks and when the checks were written.  Testifies to attempting to speak with the defendant regarding the accusations.  Cross-examination by Attorney Nolan-Plutchak.  Re-direct by Attorney Zell.  Witness reviews copies of the checks and identifies same.  Witness reviews Exhibits 1 and 2.  Witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom.  

Officer Tammy Kubisiak is sworn and questioned by Attorney Zell.  Questions witness regarding the individuals who wrote the check to defendant.   Cross-examination by Attorney Zell.  Re-direct by Attorney Zell.  Exhibits 1 and 2 are received.  

Attorney Nolan-Plutchak makes a statement for lack of probable cause regarding identification.  Attorney Zell makes a statement.  

Court finds probable cause to believe that a felony was committed and that the defendant committed it. Bond is continued.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for May 13, 2016 at 09:00 am.
Preliminary hearing and Arraignment at 03-15-2016 11:00 am
